        "id": 5010
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-05-12T21:27:22Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "If you write it this way the compiler may assume the memory is aligned for F, up to 32-byte.\n\nOddly in the code generation, the AVX and HSW code requires 4 byte alignment, the ARMv7 code 8 byte, and the sse2,sse41, and ARMv8 16 byte.  Looks like Clang finally got the message that unaligned loads have no downside with AVX+, but it definitely didn\u0027t do the same for the other instruction sets.\n\nProbably easier to stick to float and 4-byte alignment?\n\n  auto ptr \u003d (const float*)ctx;\n  r \u003d unaligned_load\u003cF\u003e(ptr + 0*kStride);\n  g \u003d unaligned_load\u003cF\u003e(ptr + 1*kStride);\n  b \u003d unaligned_load\u003cF\u003e(ptr + 2*kStride);\n  a \u003d unaligned_load\u003cF\u003e(ptr + 3*kStride);\n\nkStride is just sizeof(F) / sizeof(float), defined at the top of the file.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 337,
        "startChar": 4,
        "endLine": 341,
        "endChar": 15
      },
      "revId": "75c64f5ea475b2e5e5490aac8577c9d785853227",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
